NOTES_TITUS = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Bondservant" (doulos, G1401) denotes one wholly owned by a master—Paul claims the highest title of OT servants of YHWH (cf. Moses in Josh 1:2, David in Ps 89:3). "Knowledge" (epignōsis, G1922) is not mere gnōsis but a full, precise, experiential knowing. THEOLOGICAL: Paul grounds his apostleship in two coordinates: the faith of God\'s elect and the full knowledge of truth—linking election and revelation as inseparable realities.',
        2: 'GREEK: "Unlying" (apseudēs, G893) is a NT hapax legomenon, found only here. It intensifies God\'s truthfulness beyond merely "faithful"—He is by nature incapable of falsehood. "Before eternal ages" (pro chronōn aiōniōn) points to a pretemporal divine decree. THEOLOGICAL: The promise of eternal life originates in God\'s unchangeable nature before time itself, grounding salvation in the immutable counsel of God (cf. 2 Tim 1:9; Eph 1:4).',
        3: 'GREEK: "Manifested" (ephanerósen, G5319) marks the contrast between the hidden eternal purpose and its historical unveiling. "Proclamation" (kērygma, G2782) denotes the authoritative herald\'s announcement, not casual speech. TYPOLOGY: The pattern of hidden-then-revealed echoes the mystery motif in Paul (Rom 16:25-26; Col 1:26), wherein God\'s eternal plan is disclosed through appointed messengers at the appointed time.',
        5: 'HISTORICAL: Crete was a large Mediterranean island with numerous cities; its reputation for moral disorder (v. 12) made organized church leadership urgent. "Set in order" (epidiorthōsē, G1930) is a NT hapax, a compound verb suggesting correcting what remains deficient. STRUCTURE: This verse establishes the entire occasion and purpose of the letter—ecclesial order through qualified leadership.',
        7: 'GREEK: "Overseer" (episkopos, G1985) is used interchangeably with "elder" (presbyteros, v. 5), confirming that in the apostolic period these titles described the same office, not a hierarchical distinction. "Steward of God" (theou oikonomon) frames the overseer not as an autonomous ruler but as a household manager under divine authority. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The overseer functions as God\'s appointed representative in the local assembly, mirroring the stewardship pattern of delegated authority found throughout Scripture (cf. Luke 12:42; 1 Cor 4:1-2).',
        9: 'GREEK: "Holding fast" (antechomenon, G472) conveys a tenacious clinging to, as against opposition. "Sound" (hygiainousē, G5198) is a medical metaphor—literally "healthy" doctrine, implying that false teaching is a spiritual disease. THEOLOGICAL: The elder\'s dual task of positive exhortation and negative refutation presupposes a fixed doctrinal standard—the "faithful word according to the teaching"—against which all claims must be measured.',
        12: 'HISTORICAL: Paul quotes the Cretan poet-philosopher Epimenides of Knossos (ca. 6th century BC). Calling him "a prophet of their own" employs prophētēs in its broad Greek sense of an inspired spokesman, not affirming him as a biblical prophet. The paradox of a Cretan calling all Cretans liars was famous in Greek philosophical discourse (the "Epimenides paradox").',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: Paul counters proto-ascetic or Judaizing purity regulations by affirming the inherent cleanness of creation for the pure in heart (cf. Mark 7:15-19; Rom 14:14, 20). The defilement is not in external things but in the corrupted mind (nous) and conscience (syneidēsis) of the unbelieving. TYPOLOGY: This echoes Christ\'s teaching that defilement proceeds from within (Mark 7:20-23), fulfilling the new covenant promise of cleansed hearts (Ezek 36:25-27).',
        16: 'GREEK: "Worthless" (adokimoi, G96) means "failing the test, disqualified"—used of metals that fail assaying. "Abominable" (bdelyktoi, G947) is a strong LXX term associated with idolatrous defilement (cf. bdelygma in Dan 9:27; Luke 16:15). THEOLOGICAL: The chapter closes with the sharpest indictment: a profession of God contradicted by works constitutes a functional denial of Him, rendering one reprobate concerning every good work—a warning that orthodoxy without orthopraxy is empty.',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Ὑγιαινούσῃ" (hygiainousē, Strong\'s G5198) literally means "being healthy/sound" — a medical metaphor applied to doctrine. Paul uses this term repeatedly in the Pastoral Epistles (1 Tim 1:10; 2 Tim 4:3) to distinguish apostolic teaching from the diseased teachings of false instructors.',
        3: 'GREEK: "Ἱεροπρεπεῖς" (hieroprepeis, G2412) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, meaning "befitting a sacred person" or "reverent as befits a temple." The compound of hieros (sacred) and prepō (fitting) evokes priestly comportment. "Καλοδιδασκάλους" (kalodidaskalous, G2567) is also a NT hapax, a compound meaning "teachers of what is beautiful/good."',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The purpose clause "that the word of God be not blasphemed" (ἵνα μὴ ὁ λόγος τοῦ θεοῦ βλασφημῆται) reveals that ethical conduct among believers carries a missional dimension. Dishonorable living causes outsiders to speak evil against God\'s word itself. This echoes the OT concern that Israel\'s conduct among the nations either honored or profaned God\'s name (Isa 52:5; Ezek 36:20-23).',
        10: 'GREEK: "Κοσμῶσιν" (kosmōsin, G2885) means "to adorn, arrange, make beautiful" — from which English "cosmetic" derives. The striking image is that faithful living "adorns" or "beautifies" the doctrine of God. "Νοσφιζομένους" (nosphizomenous, G3557) means "to pilfer, embezzle, keep back for oneself" — the same verb used of Ananias and Sapphira in Acts 5:2-3.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Ἐπεφάνη" (epephanē, G2014) is an aorist passive of epiphainō, meaning "appeared, was manifested." This term carried imperial overtones in the Greco-Roman world, used for the visible manifestation of a deity or the official arrival of an emperor. Paul subverts this by declaring that God\'s saving grace — not Caesar — has made its divine epiphany to all humanity. TYPOLOGY: The appearance of grace echoes the Shekinah theology of God\'s visible glory manifesting among his people (Exod 40:34-35; Isa 60:1-2).',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse is among the strongest affirmations of Christ\'s deity in the NT. The Greek construction "τοῦ μεγάλου θεοῦ καὶ σωτῆρος ἡμῶν Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ" follows the Granville Sharp rule: a single article governs both "God" and "Savior," identifying them as one referent — Jesus Christ is here called "our great God and Savior." GREEK: "Ἐπιφάνειαν" (epiphaneian, G2015) refers to Christ\'s second appearing in glory, forming a deliberate parallel with the first epiphany of grace in v.11. The "blessed hope" (μακαρίαν ἐλπίδα) is not mere optimism but the assured expectation of eschatological consummation.',
        14: 'TYPOLOGY: "Λυτρώσηται" (lytrōsētai, G3084) means "to redeem, ransom" — evoking the Exodus redemption where God purchased Israel from bondage (Exod 6:6; Deut 7:8). "Λαὸν περιούσιον" (laon periousion) directly echoes the LXX of Exodus 19:5 and Deuteronomy 14:2, where Israel is called God\'s "treasured/peculiar possession." Christ now constitutes for himself a new covenant people through his self-offering, fulfilling the typological pattern of Israel\'s redemption. GREEK: "Ζηλωτὴν" (zēlōtēn, G2207) means "one who is zealous," carrying connotations of passionate devotion — this redeemed people is characterized not by passive reception but by active zeal for good works.',
        15: 'GREEK: "Ἐπιταγῆς" (epitagēs, G2003) denotes divinely delegated authority or command — this is not personal assertiveness but apostolic commissioning. "Περιφρονείτω" (periphroneitō, G4065) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "to think around, think beyond, despise, disregard" — stronger than the more common kataphroneō, suggesting an active looking past or dismissal of Titus\'s authority. Compare Paul\'s similar charge to Timothy (1 Tim 4:12).',
    },
    3: {
        4: 'GREEK: "chrēstotēs" (χρηστότης, Strong\'s G5544) denotes goodness or kindness in active benevolence. "Philanthrōpia" (φιλανθρωπία, G5363) literally means "love toward mankind" — a rare NT term (also Acts 28:2), here ascribed to God himself. "Epephanē" (ἐπεφάνη) is an aorist passive of "epiphainō," meaning "appeared" or "was manifested," the same root as "epiphany," carrying theophanic weight — the divine breaking into the visible realm.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse is among the most concentrated soteriological statements in the NT. Salvation is explicitly grounded not in works of righteousness performed by humans but in God\'s mercy alone. "Palingenesia" (παλιγγενεσία, G3824) is a rare term occurring only here and Matt 19:28 in the NT; it means "regeneration" or "new birth" — here describing the individual believer\'s renewal, whereas in Matthew it refers to the cosmic renewal. The coupling of "washing" (loutrón) with "regeneration" and "renewal of the Holy Spirit" links baptismal imagery with pneumatological transformation (cf. John 3:5, Ezek 36:25-27).',
        6: 'TYPOLOGY: The pouring out (ekchéō) of the Spirit echoes Joel 2:28-29 (LXX 3:1-2), fulfilled at Pentecost (Acts 2:17-18, 33). The mediatorial role of Jesus Christ as the one "through whom" the Spirit is poured connects to his ascension and enthronement as Lord. Note that God the Father is called "Savior" in v4 and Jesus Christ is called "Savior" here in v6, affirming a shared divine identity in the work of salvation.',
        7: 'GREEK: "Dikaiōthentes" (δικαιωθέντες) is an aorist passive participle — "having been justified" — indicating a completed divine action upon the believer. "Klēronomoi" (κληρονόμοι, G2818) means "heirs," drawing on the OT concept of inheritance (klēros) given to God\'s people (cf. Rom 8:17, Gal 3:29). The phrase "hope of eternal life" (elpída zōēs aiōniou) frames the inheritance as eschatological — already legally secured but awaiting full consummation.',
        8: 'STRUCTURE: "Pistos ho logos" (Faithful is the word) is one of the Pastoral Epistles\' distinctive formulae (cf. 1 Tim 1:15, 3:1, 4:9; 2 Tim 2:11), marking what precedes (vv3-7) as a creedal or hymnic confession of established apostolic teaching. Paul charges Titus to "affirm strongly" (diabebaioûsthai, G1226, a rare intensified compound) so that right doctrine produces right practice — "good works" (kalōn ergōn) being the fruit, never the root, of salvation.',
        10: 'GREEK: "Hairetikon" (αἱρετικόν, G141) is a hapax legomenon in the NT. It derives from "hairesis" (a choosing, faction, sect) and denotes one who causes division by promoting factious opinions. This is the origin of the English word "heretic," though in context it emphasizes the divisive social behavior as much as doctrinal error. The measured process — a first and second warning before rejection — reflects the principle of ecclesial discipline seen also in Matt 18:15-17.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Exestraptai" (ἐξέστραπται, perfect passive of ekstrephō) means "has been turned inside out" or "perverted" — the perfect tense indicating a settled, corrupted state. "Autokatakritos" (αὐτοκατάκριτος, G843) is another hapax legomenon meaning "self-condemned" — the factious person\'s own persistence after warning serves as the evidence of their condemnation, requiring no external judicial verdict.',
    },
}